<BaseLayout
  title="Prof. Young-Min Kim · SKKU-STEM Lab"
  description="Curriculum vitae of Prof. Young-Min Kim, principal investigator of the SKKU-STEM Laboratory at Sungkyunkwan University."
>
  <div class="section-stack pb-24 md:pb-32">
    {/* ─────────────── Page header ─────────────── */}
    <section class="container-page pt-12 md:pt-20">
      <div class="container-prose">
        <p class="font-mono text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.16em] text-coral">
          <a
            href="/people"
            class="text-ink/60 hover:text-coral transition-colors"
          >
            People
          </a>
          <span aria-hidden="true" class="mx-1.5 text-ink/30">/</span>
          Principal Investigator
        </p>

        <h1
          class="mt-6 font-display font-normal tracking-tight text-5xl md:text-6xl leading-[1.05]"
        >
          김영민
        </h1>
        <p
          class="mt-3 font-display text-2xl md:text-3xl text-ink/65 italic font-normal"
        >
          Young-Min Kim
        </p>

        <p class="mt-7 text-base md:text-lg text-ink/80 leading-relaxed">
          Professor &middot; Department of Energy Science<br />
          Sungkyunkwan University &middot; Suwon 16419, Republic of Korea
        </p>

        <p
          class="mt-8 font-serif text-lg md:text-xl text-ink/90 leading-relaxed"
        >
          Young-Min Kim is a Professor in the Department of Energy Science at
          Sungkyunkwan University, Korea. He received his Ph.D. (2010) in
          Materials Science and Engineering from KAIST, Korea, and worked as a
          researcher at the Korea Basic Science Institute (KBSI) for 14 years,
          including during his Ph.D. studies. From 2010 to 2013, he was a
          postdoctoral fellow and visiting scientist in the STEM group at Oak
          Ridge National Laboratory, where he developed expertise in
          aberration-corrected scanning transmission electron microscopy (STEM)
          and transition metal oxide thin films. His research group focuses on
          the atomic-scale structural and chemical characterization of
          functional nanomaterials and thin films using advanced STEM
          techniques, including electron energy-loss spectroscopy (EELS),
          energy-dispersive X-ray spectroscopy (EDX), four-dimensional STEM
          (4D-STEM), and electron tomography. A central theme of his recent
          work is the integration of these multimodal microscopy capabilities
          with machine learning and deep learning frameworks, enabling
          quantitative and high-throughput analysis of complex material
          systems.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    {/* ─────────────── Education ─────────────── */}
    <section
      id="education"
      class="container-page scroll-mt-12 md:scroll-mt-20"
    >
      <div class="container-prose">
        <h2
          class="font-mono text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.16em] text-ink/60 pb-4 border-b border-ink/15"
